<subSubSection id="52263CFFBD33E0A250A9D1FBEAA09C6E" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="816E51B64F0A05023C91F11530791E6B" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="73D7FC0D61090B48F8CB161E96006864" family="Megachilidae" higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="(Callomegachile)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Callomegachile">Callomegachile</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3E85B1020AA5826F85A9AF3048968A50" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2CC3FA38AA9D4F76D3359CD85F940EDE" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis and description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="84BE6A80BFCC18F4E218D20F4F3E4F40" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
In the few species present in the Palearctic, the preoccipital carina is always well developed and constitutes a good diagnostic trait. Females: Females can be recognized by the mandible without cutting edges and by the dull mandibular surface with comparatively few punctures or ridges [the mandible is also dull in some 
<taxonomicName id="A52957EF365FB403A7FC0C3B3C0EC871" lsidName="(Chalicodoma)" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Chalicodoma">Chalicodoma</taxonomicName>
of the 
<taxonomicName id="D2815D24EF18BBA0DBE8586B4F13E539" lsidName="montenegrensis" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="montenegrensis">montenegrensis</taxonomicName>
group, and to some extend in 
<taxonomicName id="CE8B0D67556609531462B5C3626D1CCE" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile (Pseudomegachile) foersteri" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foersteri" subGenus="Pseudomegachile">Megachile (Pseudomegachile) foersteri</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="D8CC5F2F86113855266E5AC3EC9949C4" originalValue="GerstÃ¤cker">Gerstaecker</normalizedToken>
, 1869 (Fig. 23)]. The clypeus is always modified in the species of 
<taxonomicName id="1C9EAA80AFFA1FE8D2B7858C0F9FC95B" lsidName="(Callomegachile)" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Callomegachile">Callomegachile</taxonomicName>
present in the Palearctic, either broadly truncate, with truncation wide, shiny, vertical or overhanging the base of the labrum (Fig. 18). Males: Males of the species present in the Palearctic always have a front coxal tooth and a quadrate projection along the inferior margin of the mandible. In many 
<taxonomicName id="89066784158BFFEEFA2C63939D6E731D" lsidName="(Callomegachile)" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Callomegachile">Callomegachile</taxonomicName>
(but not in 
<taxonomicName id="B87F7235A12AB6DCF989B0AE01E65045" genus="M." lsidName="M. sculpturalis" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="sculpturalis">M. sculpturalis</taxonomicName>
Smith, 1853), the first segment of the front tarsi forms a ventral concavity. The preapical carina of T6 is entire, without denticulation. The clypeus is mostly glabrous basally and with a dense fringe of hairs apically; in most other Palearctic 
<taxonomicName id="FAF00479008FC5422B88ACA9A00EB955" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megachile</taxonomicName>
, the clypeus is entirely covered by hairs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DE6FA3BA09D4322B8648C2290262DB03" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="species composition">
<paragraph id="DC95F56AB59543915299FFFFC064AA3C" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Species composition.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C74C3F9BA3EB4D5B205DCAB2DA997A9B" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="067449C0D8CEB9AC162C1AE0CD60A8E0" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile sculpturalis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sculpturalis">Megachile sculpturalis</taxonomicName>
, an Oriental species, has recently been introduced to western Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="4DDFAB4EAE8D125BF468E1D7B6B8C007" author="Vereecken, N" journalOrPublisher="Osmia" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="4 - 6" title="Premieres donnees sur la presence de l'abeille asiatique Megachile (Callomegachile) sculpturalis SMITH (Hymenoptera, Megachilidae) en Europe" url="http://oabeilles.net/wordpress/osmia/osmia-numeros-entiers" volume="3" year="2009">Vereecken and Barbier 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="81E108AF155273D87B263669F47602AA" author="Amiet, F" journalOrPublisher="Entomo Helvetica" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="157 - 159" title="Die Blattschneiderbiene Megachilesculpturalis Smith, 1853 (Hymenoptera, Apidae) nun auch in der Schweiz." volume="5" year="2012">Amiet 2012</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A00F206FC60E13E7B27171B0A6D76CBB" author="Quaranta, M" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Insectology" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="287 - 293" title="A new species for the bee fauna of Italy: Megachilesculpturalis continues its colonization of Europe." volume="67" year="2014">Quaranta et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="50CCE10F4AAD840EE8F0014629951121" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Eucera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="3 - 10" title="Megachilesculpturalis Smith 1853 (Hymenoptera, Apidae), a new species for the bee fauna of Germany, now north of the Alps" url="http://www.wildbienen.info/eucera/index.php" volume="9" year="2015">Westrich et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
); otherwise, only a few species of 
<taxonomicName id="3F3596136133FCB8471A14D1C2AD5B1E" lsidName="(Callomegachile)" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Callomegachile">Callomegachile</taxonomicName>
occur on the Arabian Peninsula, including 
<taxonomicName id="4A5CC9BFA53283ABAF5E754F3B6B608E" genus="M." lsidName="M. simonyi" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="simonyi">M. simonyi</taxonomicName>
Friese, 1903 and 
<taxonomicName id="F56AC0119C9E31640D1DE4B5BFDA3ED4" genus="M." lsidName="M. cephalotes" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="cephalotes">M. cephalotes</taxonomicName>
Smith, 1853 among others. At least two further species occur on the Arabian Peninsula; they probably belong to previously described African species. As mentioned above, 
<taxonomicName id="F2F988DF5FF4CF75FDAFB66330F40616" genus="M." lsidName="M. breviceps" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="breviceps">M. breviceps</taxonomicName>
likely does not belong to the Palearctic fauna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="893A0495979C6C66281C8EAECEE6778D" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="A3D450B7B6B43D8B8EAC5C68C05B0772" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A366303AFE78F024709F8CFD84950BD4" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Most species of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="CE346EEC90293BD6108A5F649A03D403" lsidName="(Callomegachile)" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Callomegachile">Callomegachile</taxonomicName>
investigated so far predominantly use resin to build their nests (
<bibRefCitation id="B0CD7FC4A7444CED1D04859CC63E41F1" author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, Maryland" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" title="The Bees of the World, second edition." year="2007">Michener 2007</bibRefCitation>
), although other materials (wood chips, mud or even leaf fragments) are sometimes used (
<bibRefCitation id="911C37DAEA0858C3B8EB75980A3C8A59" author="Piel, O" journalOrPublisher="Notes d'Entomologie Chinoise" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 8" title="Nidification de Megachilemonticola Smith, chez Xylocoparufipes Sm. f, pictifrons Sm. m." volume="5" year="1930">Piel 1930</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4CC94134913C2DCB6B1BEE16D864E57B" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile sculpturalis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sculpturalis">Megachile sculpturalis</taxonomicName>
nests in existing cavities in wood and uses resin to separate the cells; the nest plug is also built with resin but sometimes covered with a thin layer of mud (
<bibRefCitation id="CBBD5C240C53BF93841560FBAE9E2D87" author="Quaranta, M" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Insectology" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="287 - 293" title="A new species for the bee fauna of Italy: Megachilesculpturalis continues its colonization of Europe." volume="67" year="2014">Quaranta et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="4225080F855AF3B3FD8DAA0B45BA45A2" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Eucera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="3 - 10" title="Megachilesculpturalis Smith 1853 (Hymenoptera, Apidae), a new species for the bee fauna of Germany, now north of the Alps" url="http://www.wildbienen.info/eucera/index.php" volume="9" year="2015">Westrich et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Whether mud is also used for the cell partitions is unclear. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName id="F1B98954FEDCF4496CB74A4AE229EFA8" genus="M." lsidName="M. cephalotes" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="cephalotes">M. cephalotes</taxonomicName>
appears to build entire cells with mud; the cells are placed in hollow stems (
<bibRefCitation id="A87A95880B60239B6783E43CDA379586" author="Gupta, RK" journalOrPublisher="Mellifera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="53 - 64" title="Nesting biology of Megachile (Callomegachile) cephalotes Smith, a solitary bee that nests in castor sticks (Hymenoptera, Megachilidae)." volume="4" year="2004">Gupta et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
). Apparently, a &quot;brown-colored detachable membranous layer&quot; (
<bibRefCitation id="6508B7EDCAF3A5CD4BF77D363366DC1C" author="Gupta, RK" journalOrPublisher="Mellifera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="53 - 64" title="Nesting biology of Megachile (Callomegachile) cephalotes Smith, a solitary bee that nests in castor sticks (Hymenoptera, Megachilidae)." volume="4" year="2004">Gupta et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
: 58) lines the inside of the mud walls, but it is unclear what this layer refers to as it exhibits a nipple-shaped projection apically, which seems to refer to the cocoon. The floral choices of the widely polylectic species 
<taxonomicName id="80FC04AB10706099478EE1D5040E2AC0" genus="M." lsidName="M. sculpturalis" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="sculpturalis">M. sculpturalis</taxonomicName>
have been studied using pollen analyses (
<bibRefCitation id="D4FDBB0238141549A290B5BA2BBD46CF" author="Quaranta, M" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Insectology" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="287 - 293" title="A new species for the bee fauna of Italy: Megachilesculpturalis continues its colonization of Europe." volume="67" year="2014">Quaranta et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="AC8CBA24524165F0B129198505E8A0FC" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Eucera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="3 - 10" title="Megachilesculpturalis Smith 1853 (Hymenoptera, Apidae), a new species for the bee fauna of Germany, now north of the Alps" url="http://www.wildbienen.info/eucera/index.php" volume="9" year="2015">Westrich et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
